A simple text-based Tic-Tac-Toe game implemented in C++. The game allows two players to take turns playing as either 'X' or 'O' on a 3x3 grid. The game continues until one player wins, or the board is full and the game results in a draw. Players can choose to play again after a game ends.

Features
2-player turn-based gameplay.
Board is displayed after every move.
Automatically detects and announces the winner.
If the game ends in a draw, it notifies the user.
After each game, players can choose to play again or exit.


Files
TicTacToe.h: Header file containing the class definition and method declarations.
TicTacToe.cpp: Implementation file where all the game logic is defined.
main.cpp: Main program entry point. Starts the game and handles user input for replaying.


Game Flow
The game initializes with an empty 3x3 grid.
Players take turns to make a move by entering a row and column (both between 0 and 2).
    The board is displayed after each move.
    The game checks for a winner after every move.
If a player wins, the game announces the winner and ends.
If the board is full and no player has won, the game ends in a draw.
After the game ends, the player is asked if they would like to play again:
Enter 'Y' to play again.
Enter 'N' to exit the game.


